    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#haynes1951"/>, pp. <citedRange>45-46</citedRange> (ph.,dr.)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>111250</citedRange></bibl>. 
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#jmr2010a"/>, pp. <citedRange>225-226</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>60.1832</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#jmr-kenrick2015"/>, p. <citedRange>76</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="ruler" key="Berenice II"><name nymRef="#Βερενίκη"><expan><abbr><hi rend="ligature">Βε</hi></abbr><ex>ρενίκη</ex></expan></name></persName>
                </ab></div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
                <p>Bérénice.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Berenice.</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
                <p>Berenice.</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>A similar item is <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr111200</ref> found at Berenike.</p>
                <p>The present arrow-head was presented to the British Museum as having been found
                    at Cyrene. Was it really found in this city or is Cyrene used, as often, in a
                    broad sense for Cyrenaica? Whatever the answer, we may hold for plausible that it
                    belonged to the bodyguard of queen Berenice II.</p>
                <p/>
            </div></body>
